{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.4.2 Quick Augments\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 While an {\b augment contest} before the main {\b contest} can be dramatic and exciting, it does also slow down the flow of play. An alternative approach, called a {\b quick augment}, alleviates this by replacing rolling with a bonus equal to one-fifth of the {\b augmenting rating}. If your GM accepts your proposal for an {\b augment}, simply divide the {\b augmenting ability rating} by five, round down if necessary, and add the modifier as a bonus to your {\b ability} in the upcoming {\b contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It is at your GM\u8217's discretion whether to roll {\b augments} or use {\b quick augments}. Your GM may choose one preferred approach and use it in every instance, or choose one or the other on a case-by-case basis based on interest and flow of play.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.4.3 Plot Augments\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A plot {\b augment} occurs when your GM decides that your {\b victory} over a previous {\b story obstacle} is sufficiently relevant to the {\b contest} at hand as to warrant a bonus much like a supporting {\b ability} can. The previous {\b contest} need not have been immediately prior to the current one, as long as its {\b outcome} remains relevant. The magnitude of a plot {\b augment} can be +3, +6, +9, or +M. The more challenging the previous {\b contest} was and the more relevant that {\b victory} is to the current challenge, the higher the {\b augment}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 3. Character Creation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The first step in creating your character is to come up with a concept that fits in with the genre of game that your GM intends to run. With that, you can assign {\b abilities}, {\b ratings} for those {\b abilities}, and if required {\b flaws}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In addition, you will want to give your character a name, and provide a physical description. We recommend focusing on three physical things about your PC that others would immediately notice, over anything more detailed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 3.1 As-You-Go Method\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Concept\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The concept is a brief phrase, often just a couple of words that tells the GM and other players what you do and how you act. Start with a noun or phrase indicating your {\b occupation} or area of expertise, and modify it with an adjective suggesting a {\b distinguishing characteristic}, a personality trait that defines you in broad strokes:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab haughty priestess\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab hotshot lawyer\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab nai\u776?ve warrior\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab noble samurai\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab remorseful assassin\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab sardonic ex-mercenary\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab slothful vampire\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Now provide your character with a name.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab If the series uses other {\b keywords}, such as those for culture or religion, you may gain one for free.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab When events in the story put you in a situation where you want to overcome a {\b story obstacle}, make up an applicable {\b ability} on the spot. The first time you use an {\b ability} (including the two you start play with), assign a {\b rating} to it. This may be a {\b breakout ability} from a {\b keyword}. You are restricted to only one {\b sidekick}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab If you want, describe {\b flaws}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 6.\tx360\tab Once you have 12 {\b abilities} (including the two for character concept), and up to three {\b flaws} you are done creating your character.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 3.2 Assigning Ability Ratings\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You have now defined your {\b abilities}. These tell everyone what you can do. Now assign numbers to each {\b ability}, called {\b ratings}, which determine how well you can do these things.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Assign a starting {\b rating} of 17 to the {\b ability} you find most important or defining. Although most players consider it wisest to assign this {\b rating} to their {\b occupation}, which is usually a {\b keyword}, you don\u8217't have to do this. Assign a {\b rating} of 17 to your {\b distinguishing characteristic}. In some cases, you may treat your {\b distinguishing characteristic} as a {\b breakout ability} from a {\b keyword} in this case, treat it as a +4.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 All other {\b abilities} start at a {\b rating} of 13.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Now spend up to 20 points to increase any of your various {\b ratings}, including {\b keywords}. Each point spent increases a {\b rating} by 1 point. You can\u8217't spend more than 10 points on any one {\b ability}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some genre packs may require you to have additional {\b keywords} that reflect the setting. These additional {\b keywords} come from the 12 {\b ability} allowance, so in many genres you will have fewer wildcard {\b abilities} but better fit the setting.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 3.3 Keywords\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You may build your PC around one or more {\b keywords}. A {\b keyword} gives you a package deal: you get a number of {\b abilities} by selecting a pre-existing character concept, which the player then modifies.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Keywords} are best suited for use as the PC\u8217's {\b occupation}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In certain genres, you may require multiple {\b keywords}: for example, one for {\b occupation}, another for species or culture, and perhaps a third for religious affiliation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Here are two ways to handle {\b keywords}. If in doubt, choose Umbrella.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Keywords as Packages}: Treat {\b keywords} simply as shorthand for a package of {\b abilities}. These can be increased together during character creation, but are too unrelated to increase together during a game. You are still free to use the {\b keyword} as an {\b ability}, and in fact may prefer to write only the specific {\b abilities} they\u8217've improved on their character sheet.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Keywords as an Umbrella}: Treat {\b keywords} both as raisable {\b abilities} and as a collection of more specific {\b abilities}. This approach keeps the character sheet from getting too cluttered but encourages specialization. If your character is particularly good at an aspect of that keyword, you create a {\b breakout ability} under the {\b keyword} at a {\b bonus} from the {\b rating} of the {\b keyword} you write these specialized {\b breakout abilities} under the {\b keyword}, along with how much they\u8217've improved from the {\b keyword}:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Detective 17 Forensics +2 Handgun +1\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In this example, whilst the {\b rating} for most {\b contests} in which Detective was an appropriate {\b tactic} would be 17, for contests involving Forensics it would be 19, and for those involving firing a handgun it would be 18.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In some settings, an {\b ability} may be listed in more than one of a PC\u8217's {\b keywords}. Choose only one to detail it under.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 3.3 Flaws\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You may assign up to three {\b flaws} to their PC. Common flaws include:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Personality traits: surly, petty, compulsive.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Physical challenges: blindness, lameness, diabetes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Social hurdles: outcast, ill-mannered, hated by United supporters.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Flaws} are assigned a {\b rating} equivalent to your {\b abilities}. The first {\b flaw} is rated at the highest {\b ability}, the second shares the same {\b rating} as the second-highest {\b ability}, and the third equals the lowest {\b ability}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Certain {\b keywords} include {\b flaws}. {\b Flaws} gained through {\b keywords} do not count against the limit of three chosen {\b flaws}. All {\b flaws} after the third are given the same {\b rating} as the third {\b ability}. You may designate {\b flaws} from {\b keywords} as your first or second-ranked {\b flaw}. When {\b flaws} manifest during play, your GM places you in a {\b contest} against them, and rolls their associated {\b ratings} as {\b resistances} to your efforts. This method applies to {\b flaws} that primarily present you with additional {\b story obstacles} to overcome.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM may decide during play that certain {\b flaws} are better expressed as {\b penalties} to your attempts to overcome other {\b resistances}. Divide the value by 5 and round (a {\b flaw} of 19 imposes a \u8211-4 {\b penalty}). This is appropriate where the player specifies that your {\b ability} to solve problems drops under certain specific conditions. Examples might include:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Tongue-tied in large gatherings.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Lousy with a stick shift.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Can\u8217't stand snakes.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 4. Simple Contests\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Simple contest}s are the default resolution method for all {\b story obstacles}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 4.1 Simple Contest\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 4.1.1 Procedure\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Your GM {\b frames the contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab You choose a {\b tactic}, and figure your PC\u8217's {\b target number} ({\b TN}) using the {\b rating} and any {\b modifiers}. The PCs {\b TN} is the {\b rating} of their {\b ability}, plus or minus {\b modifiers} the GM may give you.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Your GM determines the {\b resistance}. If two PCs contend, your opponent figures their {\b TN} as described in step 2.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Roll a d20 to determine your {\b success or failure}, then apply any {\b bumps}. Your GM does the same for the {\b resistance}. Compare your rolled number with your {\b TN} to see how well you succeeded or failed with your {\b ability}. Remember to apply any {\b bumps} from {\b masteries} or {\b hero points}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab Determine {\b victory} or {\b defeat}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 6.\tx360\tab Describe the {\b outcome} based on the {\b story obstacle}.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 4.2 Group Simple Contest\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the {\b group simple contest}, multiple participants take part in a {\b simple contest}. Each of you in your group conducts an individual {\b simple contest} against the GM, and the {\b outcomes} for each side are collated to determine the victor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A {\b group simple contest} may pit all of you against a single {\b resistance}, representing one {\b story obstacle}. Alternatively, a {\b group simple contest} may be a series of paired match-ups between two groups of contestants. If you are forced to participate in more than one {\b contest}, then you face the standard multiple opponent {\b penalties}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 4.2.1 Procedure\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Your GM {\b frames the contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab You choose a {\b tactic}, and figure your PC\u8217's {\b target number} ({\b TN}) using the {\b rating} and any {\b modifiers}. Your {\b TN} is the {\b rating} of their {\b ability}, plus or minus {\b modifiers} the GM may give you.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Your GM determines the {\b resistance}. If two PCs contend, your opponent figures their {\b TN} as described in step 2.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab For each of your group, roll a d20 to determine your {\b success or failure}, then apply any {\b bumps}. Your GM does the same for the {\b resistance}. Compare your rolled number with your {\b TN} to see how well you succeeded or failed with your {\b ability}. Remember to apply any {\b bumps} from {\b masteries} or {\b hero points}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab Determine the number of {\b Outcome Points (OPs)} scored by the victor in the {\b contest} from the {\b group simple contest} table. On a tie the {\b victory} goes to the {\b better roll}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 6.\tx360\tab Sum the {\b OPs} gained for each side.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 7.\tx360\tab The side with the highest number of {\b OPs} is the victor in the {\b contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 8.\tx360\tab Describe the {\b outcome} based on the agreed {\b prize}.\sa180\par}
