{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 6. Relationships\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Abilities may represent your relationship to NPCs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 6.1 Supporting Characters\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Many relationships connect you to NPCs controlled by the GM.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you try to use one of these relationships to solve a problem, your {\b tactic} is your relationship {\b ability}. You can\u8217't simply go to the {\b supporting character} you have a relationship with, stick them with the problem, and expect to see it solved.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you succeeds, the {\b supporting character} helps you solve the problem. If you fail, they don\u8217't. As with any {\b ability}, you must still specify how the NPC goes about overcoming the {\b story obstacle}. Calls on relationships are almost always {\b simple contests}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In crucial situations, it may seem dramatically inappropriate for you to solve a problem indirectly, by working through others. Your GM can expose the {\b supporting character} to serious risk. If the character dies or otherwise suffers a change of status that renders them useless to you, you permanently lose the relationship {\b ability}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Before putting {\b supporting characters} at serious risk, your GM should make sure the players understand the magnitude of the possible consequences.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When {\b supporting characters} undertake significant risk, the {\b supporting character} may suffer a {\b consequence of defeat} commensurate with the level of the {\b defeat} in the {\b contest}. Or it may simply be your relationship that is damaged or destroyed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 6.2 Allies\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An {\b ally} is a character of roughly the same level of accomplishment as you, often in the same or a similar line of work. For every favor you ask of them they\u8217'll ask one of you. These reciprocal favors will be roughly equivalent in terms of risk, time commitment, resistance class, and inconvenience.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 6.3 Patrons\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Patrons} enjoy greater access to assets than you, either through personal ownership (as in a Merchant Prince) or authority (as in the governor of a province). They may lend you advice or provide them with assets but are too busy and important to personally perform tasks for you. They may hire you to do jobs, or issue orders within a command structure to which you both belong.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you roll your {\b patron} relationship, your GM adjusts the resistance class depending on what you have done for them lately.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 6.4 Contacts\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A {\b contact} is a specialist in an {\b occupation}, skill, or area of expertise. {\b Contacts} provide your information and perform minor favors, but will expect information or small favors from you in return.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can describe a {\b contact} as being a particular individual, or as a group of similar individuals.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 6.4.1 Occupational Contacts\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Any {\b occupational keyword} can be treated as a source of {\b contacts}. However, using an {\b occupational keyword} as a source of {\b contacts} will always be a {\b stretch}. To more reliably draw on particular {\b contacts} associated with your occupation, you should take an explicit ability. Use a {\b breakout ability} if you are using {\b umbrella keywords}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 6.5 Followers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A {\b follower} is a {\b supporting character} that travels with you and contributes on a regular basis to your success.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two types of followers: {\b sidekicks} and {\b retainers}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Followers} need not be people, or even sentient beings: you can write up a spirit guardian, trusty robot, or companion animal as a {\b follower}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 6.5.1 Sidekick\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A {\b sidekick} is a {\b supporting character} under your control. Most of the time they stays at your side to render assistance, but they can also go off and perform errands or missions on their own.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You should give your {\b sidekick} a name. You should, when asked, explain how the {\b sidekick} came to be your {\b follower}, and why they continue in that role.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sidekicks} start with three {\b abilities}, one rated at 16 and the others at 13. Any of these {\b abilities} may be a {\b keyword}. At least one of them should indicate a {\b distinguishing characteristic}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the sidekick is nonhuman or a member of an unusual culture, one of its three starting {\b abilities} must be its species or culture {\b keyword}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Once you have determined the {\b sidekick\u8217's} base {\b abilities}, they allocate 15 additional points between three of them, spending no more than 10 on any one {\b ability}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can improve these {\b abilities} through the expenditure of {\b hero points}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You may use any of your {\b sidekick\u8217's abilities} as your own. The {\b sidekick} can go off and do things without you.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 6.5.2 Replacing Lost Sidekicks\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As a {\b consequence of defeats} in which they participated, {\b sidekicks} can be killed or leave your service permanently.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Defeat in physical {\b contests} can lead to literal death. Metaphorical deaths from non-violent {\b contests} indicate a break you. The {\b sidekick} may angrily withdraw from your service, but is more likely to sorrowfully retire. You may be able to bring a {\b sidekick} back from metaphorical death by overcoming {\b story obstacles}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you lose a {\b sidekick}, they may create a new one without needing to spend a {\b hero point}. You must explain how the new {\b sidekick} has come to be your new {\b follower}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You may find it convenient to promote {\b retainers} to {\b sidekick} status, giving them names and personalities, with a sudden improvement in {\b abilities} and {\b ratings} to match.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 6.5.3 Retainers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A {\b retainer} is a more or less anonymous servant or helper. You may specify a single {\b retainer}, or, where appropriate to your character concept, an entire staff of them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Like any other {\b ability}, a {\b retainer} {\b ability} allows you to overcome relevant {\b story obstacles} by engaging in a {\b contest}. To model the contribution of {\b retainers}, when you are acting, you can use them to {\b augment} your {\b ability}. Your GM can rule that {\b consequences of defeat} apply to {\b retainers}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Retainers} generally regard you with all the affection and loyalty due to an employer or master. If you treat them more poorly than is expected for their culture, your GM should increase the {\b resistance class} of attempts to make use of their talents.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you lose {\b retainers} for any reason, you can replace them simply by providing a convincing explanation of how you go about it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 6.6 Relationships as Flaws\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Certain relationships with {\b supporting characters} act as {\b flaws}. They impose obligations on you, prompting your GM to present you with {\b story obstacles} you have no choice but to overcome.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 6.6.1 Dependents\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A {\b dependent} is a person, usually a family member or loved one, who requires your aid and protection. Your GM should periodically create storylines in which your {\b dependent} is endangered.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Rather than taking a {\b dependent} as a {\b flaw}, you may find it more fruitful to specify the nature of your relationship as an {\b ability}, such as {\i Love for Wife} or {\i Love for Son}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 6.6.2 Adversaries\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An {\b adversary} is a rival, enemy or other individual who can be relied upon to periodically disrupt your plans.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The {\b adversary\u8217's} goals are probably the opposite of yours, although they could be a bitter rival within the same community, organization, or movement.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To treat an {\b adversary} as an {\b ability}, rather than a {\b flaw}, describe your emotional response to them. Examples: {\i Hates Leonard Crisp}, {\i Fears the Electronaut}, {\i Sworn Vengeance Against Heimdall}. That way, you still inspire your GM to add the plot elements you desire, but can use your antipathy toward the enemy to {\b augment} your {\b target number}s against them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 7. Hero Points\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Hero points (HP)} are a resource that you must carefully allocate. They allow you to heighten your {\b victories} and dull your {\b defeats}. They are the currency you pay to improve your {\b abilities} over time.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 7.1 Improving Your Character\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You start each session with one {\b HP}. Any time that you take a significant action the GM can award you another {\b hero point}. The action should involve a {\b contest} but need not be successful. An action should be heroic or villainous in order to earn a {\b hero point}, not dull. Are the other players interested in what just happened? Don\u8217't trigger {\b contests} just to win {\b hero points}, your actions should drive story or character development forward.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 During a session you can spend those {\b HPs} as normal.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM should award a maximum of 5 {\b HPs} in a session to you.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Unspent {\b HPs} at the end of the session become {\b experience points (XPs)} and accumulate between sessions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you accumulate 10 {\b XPs}, you can buy an advance. An advance allows you to select two of the following. You cannot choose an element more than once.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab [] +9 to a standalone {\b ability} or breakout {\b ability}; or +6 to a {\b keyword}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab [] +6 to a standalone {\b ability} or breakout {\b ability}; or +3 to a {\b keyword}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab [] a new standalone {\b ability} at 13; or a new breakout {\b ability} at + 1\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab [] a new standalone {\b ability} at 13\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab [] Turn a stand-alone {\b ability} into a {\b keyword} by adding a new +1 breakout {\b ability} to it.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In some genres you may wish to maintain a tally of the total {\b XPs} earned as a measure of your reputation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 7.1.1 Catch-Ups\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To encourage well-rounded characters, a package deal, called a {\b catch-up}, becomes available whenever you acquire via improvement a new {\b mastery} in one of your {\b abilities} ({\b keyword} or stand-alone). Any time you one of your {\b ratings} crosses a {\b mastery} threshold (i.e.\u160?20 -> 21, 40 -> 41, etc). you may also improve up to three {\b abilities} or {\b keywords} of your choice increase by three points each, as long as the chosen {\b abilities} are currently rated five or more points lower than your newly adjusted {\b rating} in the raised {\b ability} that triggered the {\b catch-up}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You may not increase the bonus of {\b breakout abilities} under a {\b keyword} with a {\b catch-up}, nor does net effective value of a breakout {\b ability} crossing a {\b mastery} threshold trigger a {\b catch-up}. Only a {\b keyword}\u8217's base {\b rating} is considered in this context.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 7.1.2 Directed Improvements\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On occasion your GM may increase one of your {\b abilities}, by +3, +6 or +9, or give you a new {\b ability}, usually rated at 13. These are called {\b directed improvements}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Directed improvements} are usually rewards for overcoming particularly important or dramatic {\b story obstacles}. They happen immediately, rather than at session\u8217's end.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your GM will tend to use them to raise {\b abilities} that would otherwise fall behind, but should increase due to story logic, or introduce new {\b abilities} for the same reason.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 9 Appendix\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Glossary of Terms\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Ability} Anything you can apply to solve a problem or overcome an obstacle\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Advantage Point (AP)} A measure of advantage in an {\b extended contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Ally} A {\b supporting character} of roughly equal ability to your own.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b AP} Abbreviation for Advantage Point.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b AP Gifting} When you help another character, whilst uninvolved in a {\b contest}, by giving them {\b advantage points} in an {\b extended contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b AP Lending} When you help another character, whilst engaged in a {\b contest}, by lending them {\b advantage points}, in an {\b extended contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Asymmetrical Exchange} In a {\b extended contest}, where you are pressed by an opponent, but want to do something other than contend directly for the {\b prize}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Asymmetrical Round} In a {\b scored contest}, where you are pressed by an opponent, but want to do something other than contend directly for the {\b prize}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Assist} In a {\b scored contest}, if you are unengaged you may use an {\b assist} to reduce the {\b resource points} scored against another character.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Augment} Using one {\b ability} to help another {\b ability}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Automatic Victory} You have an appropriate {\b ability} and the GM feels {\b failure} is not interesting, or makes the PC looks un-heroic.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Background Event} An off-stage {\b bonus} or {\b penalty} applied to a {\b resource}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Base resistance} The TN for a {\b moderate resistance class}, from which all other {\b resistance classes} are figured as a {\b bonus} or {\b penalty}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Benefit of Victory} Long term positive modifier, because you won a {\b contest}, against a challenging opponent (not -6 or less than your {\b ability}). Usually a {\b state of fortune}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Bid} Also an {\b AP Bid} or {\b advantage point bid} is your wager in an {\b extended contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Bolster} A {\b story obstacle} to apply a bonus to a community {\b resource}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Bonus} A positive modifier.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Boost} Spending points ahead of a {\b group simple contest outcome}, to improve the victory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Bump} An increment of the {\b result} of a roll, up or down. So a bump up moves a {\b fumble}, to a {\b failure}, to a {\b success} to a {\b critical}, a bump down moves a {\b critical}, to a {\b success}, to a {\b failure} to a {\b fumble}. One step is moved per {\b bump}. It is usually the impact of a {\b hero point} or {\b mastery}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Catch-Up} When you cross a {\b mastery} threshold you can increase lesser used {\b abilities} to ensure they keep pace.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Climax} A {\b long contest} {\b story obstacle} that provides the conclusion to a story.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Contact} A {\b supporting character} who shares an {\b occupation} or interest with your character.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Contest} Where there is uncertainty as to whether a PC can overcome a {\b story obstacle} or discover a secret, then your GM can call for a contest to determine if the PC succeeds or fails. A contest may be {\b simple} (one roll) of {\b extended} (a series of rolls).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Consequences of Defeat} Long term negative modifier, because you lost a contest. Usually a {\b state of adversity}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Contest of Wherewithal} A {\b contest} that allows a {\b dying} character to complete one {\b final action}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Contest Framing} Setting the stakes of the {\b contest}, what is this conflict about. Often not the immediate aftermath of victory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Complete Defeat} No, and\u8230?. You have lost, and the impact is long-lasting, maybe even fatal or terminal.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Complete Victory} Yes, and\u8230? You have won, and the impact is long-lasting, possibly a permanent change in your favor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Credibility Test} Is it possible to perform the action without an {\b ability}, with an ordinary {\b ability}, or only with a {\b extraordinary ability}?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Crisis Test} Used to determine if a {\b resource} that has a {\b penalty} creates a crisis.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Defeat} Your {\b result} is worse than the {\b resistance\u8217's} result.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Defensive Response} In a {\b long contest} you can choose a defensive {\b tactic} which reduces the {\b resource points} you lose on a negative {\b result}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Degree of Victory or Defeat} How well did you triumph, or how badly did you fail: {\b Critical}, {\b Success}, {\b Failure}, {\b Fumble}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Dependent} A {\b supporting character} who depends on your PC.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Depletion} Use of a community {\b resource} leads to its depletion.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Directed Improvement} When your GM grants you a new {\b ability}, or an increase to an existing one, to recognize a story event.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Distinguishing Characteristic} The dominant personality {\b ability} that others recognize in a character.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Dying} A {\b state of adversity}, where the character\u8217's {\b defeat} will end their participation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Edge} In an {\b extended contest} adds to the {\b APs} lost or transferred when you win an {\b exchange}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Exchange} In an {\b extended contest} a round is divided into two {\b exchanges} where both aggressor and defender act. In a {\b group extended contest} a round consists of a sequence of {\b exchanges} where everyone acts in turn. The GM determines the order of action.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Extended Contest} A type of {\b long contest} in which you track the relative advantage one opponent has over another using {\b advantage points}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Experience Points (XP)} When you do not spend a {\b hero point} in a session it becomes an {\b experience point}, which can accumulate between sessions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Extraordinary ability} Certain genres allow player characters to have {\b abilities} that exceed human norms, these are {\b extraordinary abilities}. A genre pack normally outlines what is possible as part of its extraordinary powers framework.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Failure} Rolling over your {\b target number}. It can be a {\b fumble} or just a plain {\b failure}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Final Action} An attempt by {\b defeated}, but unengaged, PCs to re-enter an {\b extended contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Flaw} An {\b ability} that penalizes you instead of helping you.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Fumble} The worst {\b failure} {\b result}, a notable failure either due to incompetence or bad luck.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Follower} A {\b supporting character} under your control. Either a {\b sidekick} or {\b retainer}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Framing the contest} You and your GM agree on the {\b prize} for the victor, and your tactic in trying to win it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Group Chained Contest} A {\b chained contest} in which more than a pair of opponents contend for the {\b prize}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Group Extended Contest} An {\b extended contest} in which more than a pair of opponents contend for the {\b prize}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Group Scored Contest} A {\b scored contest} in which more than a pair of opponents contend for the {\b prize}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Group Simple Contest} A {\b simple contest} where one side has multiple participants.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Graduated Goals} When a contestant has a {\b primary} and {\b secondary} goal, and may have to choose between them if their {\b outcome} is not a {\b major} or {\b complete} victory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Handicap} In an {\b extended contest} subtracts from the {\b APs} lost or transferred when you win an {\b exchange}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Hero Point} Allows you to alter fate for a player character, either by a {\b bump} to their {\b result} or a {\b plot edit}. If unused, becomes an {\b experience point} at the end of the session.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Hurt} A state of adversity, a flesh wound or injured pride, heals at the end of a session.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Keyword} A single {\b ability} that encompasses a range of abilities within it, such as an {\b occupation} or culture. An {\b ability} within an {\b umbrella keyword} is a {\b break-out ability}, an {\b ability} within a {\b package keyword} is a {\b stand-alone ability}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Long Contest} A {\b contest} where we drill-down to the individual exchanges that resolve the conflict. We support {\b scored}, {\b extended}, and {\b chained contests}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Major Defeat} No, and. You have lost, and the impact is long-lasting.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Major Victory}, Yes, and. You have won, and the impact is long-lasting.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Marginal Defeat} No, but\u8230? You don\u8217't get what you want, but the damage may be mitigated.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Marginal Victory} Yes, but\u8230? You get what you want, but you may have to make a hard choice.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Modifiers} Adjustments to a {\b target number} due to circumstance.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Mastery} An {\b ability} {\b rating} that rises above 20 is said to have a {\b mastery}. {\b Masteries} cancel each other out in {\b contests}. {\b Masteries} that are not cancelled provide a {\b bump}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Minor Defeat} No\u8230? you don\u8217't get the agreed {\b prize}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Minor Victory} Yes\u8230? you get the agreed {\b prize}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Mismatched Goals} When the opposing sides in a {\b contest} want different {\b prizes}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Occupation} An {\b ability} that indicates the profession, or primary area of expertise, of your character.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Outcome} A {\b contest} has an {\b outcome}, described as a {\b victory} or {\b defeat} in obtaining the {\b prize} that was agreed in {\b contest framing} for any PCs involved.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Outcome Point} A point scored in favor one side in a {\b group simple contest}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Parting Shot} An attempt to make your opponent\u8217's {\b defeat} worse in an {\b long contest} ({\b scored} or {\b extended}), by \u8216'finishing them off\u8217'.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Patron} A {\b supporting character} with superior assets.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Penalty} A negative modifier.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Prize} What is at stake in the {\b contest}, decided during {\b framing}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rating} An ability has a rating, indicating how likely a character is to succeed at using it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Resistance} The forces opposing the PC in a conflict, or concealing a secret that must be overcome by using an {\b ability} in a {\b contest}. One of: {\b Nearly Impossible}, {\b Very High}, {\b High}, {\b Moderate}, {\b Low}, {\b Very Low}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Resistance Class} The {\b bonus} or {\b penalty} to the {\b resistance} {\b TN}, depending on the GM\u8217's interpretation of how {\i dramatically} hard the {\b story obstacle} is.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Resolution Point (RP)} In a {\b scored contest} an {\b RP} tracks the advantage one contestant has over the other.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Resource} A community {\b ability} that your PC may draw on.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Result} The {\b outcome} of a die roll against a {\b TN}. One of {\b critical}, {\b success}, {\b failure}, and {\b fumble}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Retainer} A {\b follower} of your PC who is not \u8216'fleshed out\u8217' and cannot act independently.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rising Action} A {\b scored contest} where the {\b story obstacle} is a step towards the final {\b story obstacle} of this story.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Risky Gambit} In a {\b long contest} you can take an action that puts you at more risk on defeat, but enhances victory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Round} A {\b long contest} is broken into a series of rounds, each of which is an attempt to obtain the {\b prize}. In an {\b extended contest} a round is further broken into a number of {\b exchanges} in which all participants have the chance to act.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Scored Contest} A {\b long contest} where we track the relative advantage one contestant has over another using {\b resolution points}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Sidekick} A fleshed out {\b follower} of your PC who can act independently.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Supporting Characters} Additional characters under the player\u8217's control that play a supporting role to their PC.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Simple Contest} A one roll resolution method, the default {\b contest} type, used when learning the {\b outcome} matters more than the breakdown of how you achieved it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Stand Alone Ability} An {\b ability} raised separately to a {\b keyword}. It may have been added to the character as part of a {\b package keyword}, or on its own.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b State of Adversity} How \u8216'banged up\u8217' a PC is, physically or metaphorically, following a {\b defeat}: : {\b Hurt}, {\b Injured}, {\b Impaired}, {\b Dying} and {\b Dead}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b State of Fortune} A \u8216'boost\u8217' to the PC which may be physical or metaphorical.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Story Obstacle} Something that prevents you from getting what you want, the {\b prize}. A {\b story obstacle} is the trigger for a {\b contest}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Stretch} A {\b penalty} applied to an {\b ability} because it is stretches credibility that it is a reasonable {\b tactic}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Success} Rolling under your {\b target number}. It can be a {\b critical} or just a plain {\b success}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Target Number (TN)} The number, either an {\b ability} {\b rating}, or a {\b resistance}, to roll under or equal to in order to {\b succeed}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b TN} Abbreviation for {\b Target Number}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Unrelated Action} An action when you are disengaged in a {\b long contest} that does not relate to your attempt to win the {\b prize}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Victory} Your {\b result} is a better roll than the {\b resistance}.\par}
